data.name: IC3D Budmen Face Shield
data.description:
The IC3D Budmen Face Shield is designed as a quick and low cost method to 3D print the bracket securing a clear face shield to the wearer via an elastic strap.  

Features:

+Fully covered top to prevent droplets falling onto the eyes

+Spacing off of the wearer's face to accomodate large goggles

+Large strap holes to allow for maximum flexibility of sourcing elastic bands

+Foam cushion for comfort and to prevent slippage (a towel can also be taped to the "bill")

+Designed so that 4 sets can nest on an 11x11" (280x280mm) build plate (such as Taz 6 / Workhorse) to maximize off-hours printing
data.osms_notes:
This face shield has undergone review in a clinical setting and is recommended when fabricated as instructed.

**There is an additional Dental Modification**

data.name: Prusa Face Shield
data.description:
This is a 3D printed face shield for the US. Based on the community feedback, the design was adjusted to fit an American size sheet (11 x 8.5 inches), American triple hole punch (distance 4 1/4", hole radius 1/4")

Dental Modification for Loupes and Optics: This project forks off the original to let the led attached to the front and with enough place for binocular. The light support and the 2 cable support are printed separately and glue in the placement made in the shield.
data.osms_notes: The NIH link includes PDF assembly and disinfection instructions that meet EUA Guidance requirements; Prusa added a cover to their design; this addition further protects the wearer in instances of aerosolized droplets/virus. Some hospitals or clinicians will want to have the cover due to higher risk conditions; others may not need it. Prusa added specifications regarding disinfection.

data.name: Solin Design
data.description:
Real flatpack design (now with tabs)
Laser cuts in under 2 minutes
5-pieces
Fully adjustable
Uses one material (no elastic or 3D printed parts needed)
Easy to ship in quantity since it's flat
Can be sterilized (in quantity) for reuse (depending on plastic used)
data.creator: Jeff Solin
data.osms_notes: Community use. Best for non-healthcare workers such as delivery couriers, or in crisis situations where this is the only design available.

data.name: Open Face PPE
data.description:
The Open Source Face Shield is a low cost, medical face shield designed to be quickly made using almost any flat material fabrication equipment (laser cutters, rule dies, drag knife, CNC punch, etc.), or even scissors and an office hole punch from any clear flexible material.
It requires no hardware or 3D printed parts, just two pieces of flexible clear plastic and an elastic band.
data.creator: Uriel Eisen, Andrew Eisen, Vadim Gordin, and Callil Capuozzo
data.osms_notes: Simple, three-part design requiring clear plastic film and basic hand tools. Design sits close to the face compared to other designs with a visor headband. Includes DXF files.

data.name: 3DP Indirect Ophthalmoscope Shield

data.name: Trueshape Oxymeter
data.description: During oxygen supply shortages, patients sometimes receive oxygen treatment from tanks when in-house titration systems are overloaded. This flowmeter design allows oxygen tanks to be titrated directly at the source, thus extending the oxygen supply and ensuring correct patient treatment. This practical alternative was developed during the 2021 oxygen supply crisis in India, and can be made with CNC and 3D printed parts.
data.osms_notes: This flowmeter design allows oxygen tanks to be titrated directly at the source, thus extending the oxygen supply and ensuring correct patient treatment. This practical alternative was developed during the 2021 oxygen supply crisis in India, and can be made with CNC and 3D printed parts.

data.name: RKID PAPR
data.description:
The solution is an easy to build Mask and Pump.
The Mask is constructed from:
- Shield       –   Digitally cut from PET clear sheet or a 1,5L bottle
- Foam parts   –   Laser or CNC cut 8 – 10 mm foam medium density
- 3D printing  –   Easy print-friendly parts in STL format
The Pump is constructed from:
- 3D printing   –   Easy print-friendly parts in STL format
- Foam seal    –   Laser or CNC cut foam
- Electric parts –   Standard hobby parts
The two assemblies are then linked with a standard hospital air line pipes, pool- or vacuum cleaner pipe.
The pump is drivven by a 12V DC motor (Speed: 640rpm, Stall Torque: 0.64 kg-cm, Stall Current: 770mA, Current: 38mA) an can delivers 80L/M through two P2 filter into the mask.
Battery pack is made up from 18650 Battries (3 off), housed in a 3bay battery holder
Rocker switch, 3A, 15x1omm type for the on/off
data.osms_notes: Complete unit. Includes files for 3d printed air pump, cnc cuts for foam and poly facemask, requires P2 filters.

data.name: Bunny Science PAPR
data.description:
bunnyPAPR™ is open-sourced Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) for practitioners, patients, and frontline workers who don’t have access to FDA-approved equipment.
Made with readily available components, the bunnyPAPR™ provides accessible, user-friendly, and affordable protection. Named for its dual outflow vents, bunnyPAPR™ features:
- Positive Air Pressure (fan): Makes for a superior fit. Does not require a “perfect seal.” Immune to leaks.
- Ubiquitous Filters: The same 99.99%+, FDA-approved viral filters used in hospitals. 
- Common Components: Viral filter; computer fan; USB power pack; plastic bag; 3D-printed parts (can be produced for you).
- Full Coverage: Protects the entire head and face against airborne and splash risks.
- Field Tested: Provides protection and comfort for 11+ hours.
- Reusable, Disposable, and Easily Sterilized: No problems with disinfectants making shields opaque, creating holes in gear, or exposing workers to a harmful class of chemicals for extended periods of time.
data.creator: Dr. Kuo
data.osms_notes: Requires a filter that may be difficult to source, does not appear to meet normal air flow requirements for a traditional PAPR, appears to have been designed in partnership with hospital staff.

data.name: Baseline Design Project PPE Mask
data.description: The BaselineDesign Mask was developed to solve the many design flaws of a 3D printed mask while remaining just as easy and accessible to make. The design uses readily available two-part silicone poured into a simple 3D printed mold, that's it!
data.creator: Connor Weller
data.osms_notes: Autoclavable silicone mask fabricated with a simple 3DP mold and affordable materials. Reports improved wearability when compared to other 3DP mask models.
data.category_name: Face Masks (3D Printed, Injection Molded, ETC.)

data.name: Tyvek Soft Facemask
data.description: This respirator facemask can be built of common materials plus small, easy-to-print 3D printed parts, and a small (55mm) disk of filter material. The mask is adjustable to the face, with the Tyvek forming an impermeable membrane, concentrating the breathing airflow through the filter housing. The filter housing is made of 2 identical 3D-printed parts that snap together over the filter and around the edge of a circular hole in the Tyvek. The filter material is a 55mm diameter disk of material (preferably HEPA-certified) that permits sufficient airflow. The resulting mask, when properly fitted, is protective and breathable,
data.creator: boring_pilot
data.osms_notes: Tyvek mask body with 3DP filter attachments.
data.category_name: Face Masks (3D Printed, Injection Molded, ETC.)

data.name: Ariel Rojo UNO Mask
data.description: The emergency UNO Respirator Mask was created to help fight the proliferation of the COVID-19 virus. Its design is optimized for 3D printing and includes incoming and outgoing valve ports meant to connect to various medical devices or respiratory filters.
data.creator: Ariel Rojo
data.osms_notes: Substitute for a Decathlon or Denier scuba diving mask. Files include mask, filter, splitter, connector and PEEP valve schematics.
data.category_name: Face Masks (3D Printed, Injection Molded, ETC.)

data.name: UW-DFab Non-Rebreather Mask
data.description:
This is a design for a vacuum formed non-rebreather (NRB) mask with a 3D printed connector. Our design includes:
1. A vacuum formed plastic mask
2. A printed o2 connector
3. 2 valves for the mask
4. 1 valve for the o2 connector
It does not include a component for the bag. You must provide a bag for the system to work properly.
data.creator: Jeffrey Lipton, Aidan Fay, James Shin, Scott Hudson, Flyn O’Brien
data.osms_notes: Vacuum formed, scalable design using PETG and polystyrene. Includes 3DP oxygen connector and mask valves. The receiving facility will need to provide a bag attachment for the mask to work as a non-rebreather.

data.name: Glia Tourniquet
data.description: 3D printed tourniquet to stop bleeding, especially related to penetrating injuries.
data.license: GPLv3 license- These files are also available as Creative Commons By Attribution ShareAlike if desired.
data.creator: Dr. Tarek Loubani
data.osms_notes: Trauma tourniquet to stop blood loss and preserve limb integrity post-injury. Can be also be used for small adults and pediatric patients <18 years as opposed to commercial C-A-T tourniquets which are for > 18 years only. As of Mar/05/2022, the design had been clinically tested for ABS. PETG clinical testing is pending. PETG construction is considered for emergency use cases only. Injection molding files are pending.

data.name: Western University Low-Cost Walker
data.description: "This article describes a static, four-legged walker that can be constructed from materials and fasteners commonly available from hardware stores coupled by open-source 3D-printed joints. The designs are described in detail, shared under an open-source license, and fabricated with a low-cost open-source desktop 3D printer and hand tools."
data.osms_notes: Peer-reviewed study of low-cost, customized walker designs with 3DP and hardware-store accessible components. Includes load-failure testing and recommendations for design evolutions.
